{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":1316,"record_hash":"sha256:4650e78548756c21917dfad9da9c49355d6a8d249e356bb145169c7b145e2b82","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:30:42.540Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 644f61\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1264\nOutput:\n- planning depth\n- discussed edge cases\n- follow-up questions\n\nFor this use case, turns are more valuable than whole-session links because a\nsession may span unrelated work. A review view can start from a branch, change,\nor PR, find related sessions, and then use turn evidence to highlight the likely\nrelevant parts of those sessions. Commit-centric lookup can come later by\nresolving through change or branch evidence; it does not need its own v1 index.\n\nThe important line remains: turns can provide evidence and suggestions without\nautomatically asserting durable ownership.\n\n## Proposed Hierarchy\n\nThe broader data hierarchy becomes:\n\n```text\none session -> many capture turns -> many records\n```\n\nA session remains the durable project-scoped object. A capture turn represents\none capture invocation, usually one observed agent stop-hook run. Transcript\nrecords remain the normalized conversation/tool events that `but-agentlog`\nalready stores and deduplicates.\n\nThis is deliberately not:\n\n```text\nbranch -> session -> records\n```\n\nBranches, changes, commits, and pull requests should still reference sessions or\nturns. They should not own transcript data.\n\nIn this document, \"turn\" means **capture turn** unless explicitly qualified. A\ncapture turn is the durable storage unit. UI/read paths may still render\n**conversation turns** or **provider turns** inside a capture turn, especially\nfor handoff and backfilled sessions.\n\n## What A Capture Turn Means\n\nA capture turn is the unit of \"what we observed this time.\"\n\nEvery time the capture flow runs:\n\n1. parse the transcript snapshot\n2. deduplicate against already stored record hashes\n3. append only new transcript records\n4. write a capture turn object describing this capture invocation\n5. record which transcript records belong to the turn\n6. record enough repository environment state to support later association\n\nCreate a capture turn only when capture writes at least one\n[TRUNCATED]\nfill turns are valid transcript history, but their environment snapshot is\nweaker association evidence because it only describes capture time, not the time\neach historical provider turn happened.\n\nBackfill must still be readable. Record parsing should preserve enough grouping\nmetadata for handoff and review UIs to render logical conversation turns inside\nthe backfill capture turn:\n\n- provider turn key when the source provides one\n- otherwise a derived display group based on user-message boundaries and record\n  order\n\n## Capture Turn Data\n\nA capture turn needs a stable ID for idempotent repeated capture. Given a\ncapture turn, it should be possible to find the transcript records that were\nnewly observed in that turn.\n\nTurn identity should be derived from capture content, not from time or provider\nturn ids. Use a 128-bit truncated SHA-256 value: take the first 16 bytes of the\ndigest and render them as 32 lowercase hex characters.\n\nKey formats:\n\n- session, source, and turn keys: `sha256-<32 lowercase hex chars>`\n- transcript record hashes: `sha256:<full lowercase hex digest>`\n\nThe turn-key digest input is the canonical stored strings encoded as UTF-8, with\na NUL byte between every component:\n\n```text\nsession_key NUL source_key NUL record_hash_1 NUL record_hash_2 NUL ...\n```\n\nThere is no empty-record case because a capture turn is only created after at\nleast one new transcript record is accepted.\n\nThat makes the newly accepted transcript records the identity of what this\ncapture observed. Capture timestamp and environment snapshot are turn\nattributes, not identity. This also makes retries easier: the same accepted\nrecord set maps to the same turn key.\n\nProvider-native turn identifiers should not define the durable `turn-key`.\nProviders may omit them, define turns differently, expose private/raw ids, or\ninclude many provider turns inside one first-time backfill capture. If present,\nthey can be stored as optional record-level grouping metadata, preferably as a\nsafe provider turn key rather than a raw provider id.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:30:42.540Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}